ists and engineers defined themselves as experts. Rather than claiming to be infallible, they began to portray themselves as responsible—committed to operating safely and to contributing to the well-being of the community. The volume shows that by grounding their claims to responsibility in influential ideas from the larger culture about what makes good citizens, nice communities, and moral companies, refinery scientists made it much harder for residents to challenge their expertise and thus re-established their authority over scientific questions related to the refinery's health and environmental effects.Gwen Ottinger here shows how industrial facilities' current approaches to dealing with concerned communities—approaches which leave much room for negotiation while shielding industry's environmental and health claims fromcritique—effectively undermine not only individual grassroots campaigns but also environmental justice activism and far-reaching efforts to democratize science. This work drives home the need for both activists and politically engaged scholars to reconfigure their own activities in response, in order to advance community health and robust scientific knowledge about it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnvironmental responsibilityxUnited States. 0aEnvironmental responsibilityzUnited States. 0aPetroleum industry and tradexUnited StatesxLouisianaxNew SarpyxUnited StatesxElectronic books. 0aPetroleum industry and tradezUnited States. 0aPetroleum refineriesxEnvironmental aspectsxLouisianaxNew Sarpy. 0aPetroleum refineriesxEnvironmental aspectszLouisianazNew Sarpy. 0aSocial responsibility of businessxUnited States. 0aSocial responsibility of businesszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York Univ